<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1323,1767,1905]" lastBlockId="7.[264,1323,284,571]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="46" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">
Among the material sent by Dr Carl Rettenmeyer were the 
<typeStatus box="[998,1101,1767,1793]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">holotype</typeStatus>
female and seven female 
<typeStatus box="[362,474,1805,1831]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">paratypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier. Borgmeier (1960)" authorityName="Borgmeier. Borgmeier" authorityYear="1960" box="[536,1240,1805,1831]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Homalophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epichaeta">
<emphasis box="[536,833,1805,1830]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="45">Homalophora epichaeta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[851,1240,1805,1831]" pageId="6" pageNumber="53" refString="Borgmeier, T. (1960) Gefluegelte und ungefluegelte Phoriden aus der Neotropischen Region, nebst Beschreibung von sieben neuen Gattungen (Diptera, Phoridae). Studia Entomologica, Petropolis, 3, 257 - 374." type="journal article">
Borgmeier. Borgmeier (
<number box="[1170,1231,1805,1831]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" value="1960.0">1960</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
states unequivocally that the females of this genus lack the anterior flap embraced by the front margin of abdominal tergite 
<number box="[610,626,1879,1905]" pageId="6" pageNumber="45" value="5.0">5</number>
, that is to say that they lack the dorsal abdominal glands (DAGs) that discharge between abdominal tergites 
<number box="[893,908,284,310]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
and 
<quantity box="[973,1023,284,310]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.27" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" unit="in" value="5.0">5 in</quantity>
the females of the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[264,394,321,347]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Metopinini">Metopinini</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[456,625,321,347]" pageId="7" pageNumber="53" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2003 b) The dorsal abdominal glands and the higher classification of the Phoridae (Diptera). Zootaxa, 293, 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="2003" yearSuffix="b">
Disney 
<number box="[547,610,321,347]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="2003.0">2003</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
). However, on remounting the 
<typeStatus box="[996,1047,321,347]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
series of 
<taxonomicName authority="Borgmeier" authorityName="Borgmeier" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Homalophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epichaeta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Homalophora epichaeta</emphasis>
Borgmeier
</taxonomicName>
on slides it has been found that a small flap (and DAGs) are present at the front of T 
<number box="[461,474,396,422]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
(Fig. 
<number box="[551,581,396,422]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="13.0">13</number>
) that is more substantial than that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Malloch" authorityName="Malloch" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virginiensis">
<emphasis box="[1037,1323,396,421]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Puliciphora virginiensis</emphasis>
(Malloch)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[410,510,433,459]" captionStart="FIGURES 20 – 21" captionStartId="12.[264,383,1825,1849]" captionTargetBox="[527,1071,938,1804]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[471,1119,916,1821]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 20 – 21. Puliciphora females, abdominal tergites 4 – 6: (20) P. reevesi; (21) P. v i rg i n i e n ­ sis. Scale bars = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/169852/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[477,510,433,459]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
). Therefore this species is herewith transferred to the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[264,404,471,496]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[264,404,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">Puliciphora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It was then found that these females will run to 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" box="[997,1246,471,497]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanae">
<emphasis box="[997,1153,471,496]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">P. mexicanae</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
in the most recent key to the Neotropical species of this genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[942,1111,508,534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="53" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2003 a) Seven new species of New World Puliciphora Dahl (Diptera: Phoridae) with a new key to the Neotropical species. Zootaxa, 162, 1 - 22." type="journal article" year="2003" yearSuffix="a">
Disney 
<number box="[1035,1098,508,534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" value="2003.0">2003</number>
a
</bibRefCitation>
). Consequently 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">P. mexicanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
must be synonymised with 
<emphasis box="[717,987,545,570]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="46">
<taxonomicName box="[717,983,545,570]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epichaeta">Puliciphora epichaeta</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
